Title: Introducing our Hands-On Case Study: Cadabra.com
Udemy 101
Description (if available): If you're new to Udemy, learn how to have the best experience with the Q&A feature, video controls, transcripts, captions, and reviews.

Title: Cost of the Course + AWS Budget Setup
Domain 1: Collection
Description (if available): Use Kinesis Data Streams, Kinesis Firehose, SQS, IOT, Database Migration Service, Direct Connect, and Snowball to move massive data sets where they need to be.

Title: [Exercise] Kinesis Firehose, Part 1
Description (if available): We'll build up a system to populate an S3 data lake from EC2 server data, using Kinesis Firehose.

Title: [Exercise] Kinesis Firehose, Part 2
Description (if available): We'll build up a system to populate an S3 data lake from EC2 server data, using Kinesis Firehose.

Title: [Exercise] Kinesis Firehose, Part 3
Description (if available): We'll build up a system to populate an S3 data lake from EC2 server data, using Kinesis Firehose.

Title: [Exercise] Kinesis Data Streams
Description (if available): We'll create a Kinesis stream, and use the Kinesis Agent to send data from EC2 into it - and confirm data is being successfully sent and received. This will form the basis of our "order history app" that we'll build up across future exercises in this course.

Title: Domain 2: Storage
Description (if available): Use S3, DynamoDB, and Elasticache to store data in different ways, for different usage patterns.

Title: [Exercise] DynamoDB
Description (if available): We'll continue to flesh out our "order history app" by writing our order data from a Kinesis stream into a DynamoDB table, using a Kinesis consumer app on EC2 for now to bridge the two.

Title: Domain 3: Processing
Description (if available): Use Lambda, Glue, EMR, Amazon ML, SageMaker, and Data Pipeline to process the data you've collected.

Title: [Exercise] AWS Lambda
Description (if available): We'll complete our "order history app" example by replacing our Kinesis consumer app with a Lambda function, which is serverless and more scalable.

Title: Quiz: AWS Lambda
Description (if available): Check the depth of your knowledge on AWS Lambda - you'll need to have listened carefully to the previous lectures!

Title: What is Glue? + Partitioning your Data Lake
Quiz: AWS Glue
Description (if available): Check your knowledge on some of the finer points of AWS Glue crawlers, data catalogs, and ETL jobs.

Title: Spark Integration with Kinesis and Redshift
[Exercise] Elastic MapReduce, Part 1
Description (if available): Let's use Apache Spark and it's machine learning library, MLLib, on an Amazon EMR cluster - to consume our order data in an S3 data lake, and produce product recommendations for our customers.

Title: [Exercise] Elastic MapReduce, Part 2
Description (if available): Let's use Apache Spark and it's machine learning library, MLLib, on an Amazon EMR cluster - to consume our order data in an S3 data lake, and produce product recommendations for our customers.

Title: [Quiz] EMR and the Hadoop Ecosystem
Description (if available): The world of Elastic MapReduce and the applications it can run is huge! Test your knowledge on a few of its finer points.

Title: [Exercise] Amazon Machine Learning, Part 1
Description (if available): We'll use Amazon's Machine Learning service to predict quantities for any given order, and learn the importance of cleaning your data of outliers along the way.

Title: [Exercise] Amazon Machine Learning, Part 2
Description (if available): Part 2 of our exercise to predict order quantities with a linear regression from Amazon ML.

Title: Quiz: Amazon Machine Learning and SageMaker
Description (if available): Test your knowledge of details of Amazon ML and SageMaker that may prove useful in the exam.

Title: Domain 4: Analysis
Description (if available): Use Kinesis Analytics, Amazon Elasticsearch Service, Athena, Redshift, and RDS to analyze your big data in the cloud.

Title: [Exercise] Kinesis Analytics, Part 1
Description (if available): We'll build up a more complex application that monitors our incoming order data using Kinesis Analytics. If an anomalous order rate is detected, an alarm will be sent via text message to your cell phone using Lambda and SNS.

Title: [Exercise] Kinesis Analytics, Part 2
Description (if available): We'll build up a more complex application that monitors our incoming order data using Kinesis Analytics. If an anomalous order rate is detected, an alarm will be sent via text message to your cell phone using Lambda and SNS.

Title: Quiz: Kinesis Analytics
Description (if available): Test your knowledge of the intricacies of Kinesis Analytics.

Title: [Exercise] Amazon Elasticsearch Service, Part 1
Description (if available): In this hands-on activity, we'll spin up an Amazon Elasticsearch cluster, and configure Kinesis Firehose to dump Apache web server logs into it for querying and visualization with Kibana.

Title: [Exercise] Amazon Elasticsearch Service, Part 2
Description (if available): In this hands-on activity, we'll spin up an Amazon Elasticsearch cluster, and configure Kinesis Firehose to dump Apache web server logs into it for querying and visualization with Kibana.

Title: [Exercise] Amazon Elasticsearch Service, Part 3
Description (if available): In this hands-on activity, we'll spin up an Amazon Elasticsearch cluster, and configure Kinesis Firehose to dump Apache web server logs into it for querying and visualization with Kibana.

Title: Quiz: Amazon ES
Description (if available): Test your knowledge of Amazon's Elasticsearch Service.

Title: Athena and Glue, Costs, and Security
[Exercise] AWS Glue and Athena
Description (if available): We'll use a Glue crawler to set up a Glue Data Catalog for our S3 order data, and then query it directly using Amazon Athena.

Title: Quiz: Amazon Athena
Description (if available): Test your knowledge of when to use Athena, and how.

Title: [Exercise] Redshift Spectrum, Pt. 1
Description (if available): Let's launch a Redshift cluster, and use AWS Glue to provide a schema we can use to query our S3 order data via Redshift Spectrum.

Title: Quiz: Amazon Redshift
Description (if available): The exam will expect a lot of depth on Redshift from you. Test your knowledge of the finer points.

Title: Amazon Relational Database Service (RDS) and Aurora
Domain 5: Visualization
Description (if available): Use QuickSight to visualize your data with charts and graphs, and explore alternative technologies.

Title: [Exercise] Amazon Quicksight
Description (if available): We'll set up QuickSight on top of our Redshift data warehouse, and scratch the surface of the visualizations it can produce.

Title: Quiz: Amazon Quicksight
Description (if available): Test your knowledge on the finer points of QuickSight.

Title: Domain 6: Security
Description (if available): Learn best practices for securing big data applications on AWS, using KMS, IAM, HSM, and more.

Title: Everything Else
Description (if available): Learn other important topics that are helpful on the exam, such as choosing an EC2 instance type, auto-scaling, and how different services connect to each other.

Title: Preparing for the Exam
Description (if available): Learn how to manage your time on the exam, and further materials you should study ahead of time.
